{"title_page": "Tobu Kumagaya Line", "text_new": "{{short description|Former railway line operated by Tobu Railway in Japan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width   =\n| name        = Tobu Kumagaya Line\n| native_name   = \u6771\u6b66\u718a\u8c37\u7dda\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| color       =\n| logo        =\n| logo_width  =\n| image       = Kami-Kumagaya Station 20111114 (5).jpg\n| image_width = 300px\n| caption     = Disused track of the former Tobu Kumagaya Line at [[Kami-Kumagaya Station]] in November 2011\n| type        = [[Heavy rail]]\n| system      =\n| status      =\n| locale      = [[Saitama Prefecture]]\n| start       = {{STN|Kumagaya}}\n| end         = Menuma\n| stations    = 4\n| routes      =\n| daily_ridership   =\n| open        = 1943\n| close       = 1983\n| owner       = [[Tobu Railway]]\n| operator    =\n| character   =\n| depot       = None\n| stock       = Tobu KiHa 2000 series\n| linelength  = {{Convert|10.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength =\n| tracks     = 1\n| gauge       = {{RailGauge|1067mm}}\n| electrification          = Not electrified\n| speed       =\n| elevation   =\n| map         = \n| map_state   =\n}}\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Tobu Kumagaya Line'''|\u6771\u6b66\u718a\u8c37\u7dda|T\u014dbu Kumagaya-sen}} was a 10.1&nbsp;km single-track line operated by [[Tobu Railway]], which ran from [[Kumagaya Station|Kumagaya]] to Menuma in [[Saitama Prefecture]] between 1943 and 1983.<ref name=\"asahi2010\">{{cite book |script-title=ja: \u6b74\u53f2\u3067\u3081\u3050\u308b\u9244\u9053\u5168\u8def\u7ddaNO.5 \u6771\u6b66\u9244\u9053\uff12|trans-title=Railway Line History No. 5: Tobu Railway 2| publisher = Asahi Shimbun Publications Inc| date = September 2010| location = Japan| page =24| isbn = 978-4-02-340135-8}}</ref><ref name=\"terada2003\">{{cite book| last = Terada| first = Hirokazu |script-title=ja: \u79c1\u9244\u5ec3\u7dda25\u5e74 |trans-title=25 Years of Abandoned Private Railways| publisher = JTB Can Books| date = October 2003| location = Japan| pages = 52\u201353, 167| isbn = 978-4-533-04958-3| title = \u79c1\u9244\u5ec3\u7dda25\u5e74: 36\u793e51\u7dda600km\u306e\u73fe\u5f79\u6642\u4ee3\u3068\u5ec3\u7dda\u8de1\u3092\u8a2a\u306d\u3066 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nConstruction of the line was planned during the [[Pacific War]] to provide transportation for the military supply factories located in the area. It opened on 5 December 1943, although the shortage of materials during the war meant that the rails for the line had to be procured by singling the [[Tobu Nikko Line]] between [[Kassemba Station|Kassemba]] and [[Tobu Nikko Station]]s. The original plan to extend the line beyond Menuma over the [[Tone River]] to the freight terminal at Shin-Koizumi (on the now closed Sengokugashi Freight Line extending from the [[Tobu Koizumi Line]] at [[Nishi-Koizumi Station|Nishi-Koizumi]]) was cancelled following the end of the war.<ref name=\"asahi2010\"/>\n\nThe line was not linked to any other Tobu lines, and remained unprofitable. It was finally closed on 31 May 1983.<ref name=\"asahi2010\"/>\n\nSome of the former Kumagaya Line track remains in situ between Kumagaya and [[Kami-Kumagaya Station|Kami-Kumagaya]] on the [[Chichibu Main Line]], as does one of the concrete piers for the planned Tone River bridge, on the [[Gunma Prefecture]] side of the river.<ref name=\"railfan590\"/>\n\n==Stations==\n''Source:'' <ref name=\"terada2003\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Japanese !! Distance (km) !! Passenger statistics<ref group=\"Note\">Average number of daily passengers for fiscal 1978</ref> !! Remarks\n|-\n| {{STN|Kumagaya}} || \u718a\u8c37 || align=right| 0.0 || align=right| 1,716 || Staffed<ref group=\"Note\" name=\"chichibu\">Staffed by Chichibu Railway personnel</ref>\n|-\n| {{STN|Kami-Kumagaya}} || \u4e0a\u718a\u8c37 || align=right| 0.9 || align=right| 150 || Staffed<ref group=\"Note\" name=\"chichibu\"/>\n|-\n| \u014chata || \u5927\u5e61 || align=right| 4.4 || align=right| 704 || Unstaffed\n|-\n| Menuma || \u59bb\u6cbc || align=right| 10.1 || align=right| 1,452 || Staffed\n|}\n\nNotes:\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==Rolling stock==\n[[File:Tobu-railway-Kiha2002-20110818.jpg|thumb|Preserved KiHa 2000 series diesel railcar formerly used on the Kumagaya Line, August 2011]]\nThe line was initially operated using Class B2 (ex-JNR Class 5300) [[Beyer Peacock]]-built steam locomotives (numbers 27 and 28, ex-JNR 5312 and 5313) hauling former DeHa 1 electric cars converted to non-powered passenger coaches.<ref name=\"railfan590\">{{cite magazine| last =| first =| script-title=ja: \u6771\u6b66\u9244\u9053\u718a\u8c37\u7dda\u3068\u90a3\u9808\u96fb\u6c17\u8ecc\u9053|trans-title=Tobu Kumagaya Line and Nasu Tramway|magazine=[[Japan Railfan Magazine]]| volume = 50| issue = 590|pages=128\u2013135| publisher = Koyusha Co., Ltd.| location = Japan| date = June 2010}}</ref> A fleet of three new KiHa 2000 series diesel railcars built by [[Tokyu Car]] was introduced from February 1954.<ref name=\"terada2003\"/> These were initially painted in [[JNR]]-style blue and cream, but from June 1963, they were repainted into the Tobu livery of \"royal beige\" and \"international orange\". From February 1972, the three railcars were repainted into the Tobu livery of all-over \"sage cream\".<ref name=\"terada2003\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway lines in Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tobu transit}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tobu Kumagaya Line}}\n[[Category:Lines of Tobu Railway|Kumagaya Line]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Saitama Prefecture]]\n[[Category:1067 mm gauge railways in Japan]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1943]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 1983]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former railway line operated by Tobu Railway in Japan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width   =\n| name        = Tobu Kumagaya Line\n| native_name   = \u6771\u6b66\u718a\u8c37\u7dda\n| 